<storybody><![CDATA[<p>The Indian Railways and the Power Ministry are considering a big leap towards achieving 100 per cent electrification of the entire rail network in the country. The two ministries will work together to electrify nearly 35,000 km of railway line in the next 5 to 7 years. The Power Ministry has proposed to bear the entire cost of electrification and recover the cost from railways at later stage. If the railways achieves the target, this will be more than the total length of rail line electrified since Independence.</p><p><b>IMPACT<br /></b><br />With electrification, the railways may gradually stop the production of diesel locomotives and also reduce the use of diesel as a fuel. With this, railways may be able to cut down its expenses on fuel by up to Rs 18,000 crore annually. Experts said it will also contribute to clean environment.<br /><b><br />FEASIBILITY</b></p><p>Electrification will be a daunting task. On an average, 1,350 km of rail line is electrified every year. However, cash crunch is a big factor for slow pace of work. With the power ministry's proposal to bear the entire cost, railway officials are hopeful of executing the work at a fast pace. Railway Minister Suresh Prabhu is likely to take a decision soon.</p><p><b><a target="_blank" href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/wi-fi-service-kolkata-underground-metro-rail/1/683095.html" mce_href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/wi-fi-service-kolkata-underground-metro-rail/1/683095.html">Also read: Get set for Wi-Fi service on Kolkata's underground metro rail!</a></b> </p>]]></storybody>
